[445.032849, "o", "\u001b[4mJOURNALCTL\u001b[24m(1)                                              journalctl                                             \u001b[4mJOURNALCTL\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       journalctl - Print log entries from the systemd journal\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mjournalctl \u001b[22m[OPTIONS...] [MATCHES...]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mjournalctl \u001b[22mis used to print the log entries stored in the journal by \u001b[1msystemd-journald.service\u001b[22m(8) and \u001b[1msystemd-journal-\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mremote.service\u001b[22m(8).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If called without parameters, it will show the contents of the journal accessible to the calling user, starting with the\u001b[m\r\n       oldest entry collected.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If one or more match arguments are passed, the output is filtered accordingly. A match is in the format \"FIELD=VALUE\",\u001b[m\r\n       e.g.  \"_SYSTEMD_UNIT=httpd.service\", referring to the components of a structured journal entry. See \u001b[1msystemd.journal-\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mfields\u001b[22m(7) for a list of well-known fields. If multiple matches are specified matching different fields, the log entries\u001b[m\r\n       are filtered by both, i.e. the resulting output will show only entries matching all the specified matches of this kind.\u001b[m\r\n       If two matches apply to the same field, then they are automatically matched as alternatives, i.e. the resulting output\u001b[m\r\n       will show entries matching any of the specified matches for the same field. Finally, the character \"+\" may appear as a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
