[447.742374, "o", "\u001b[Ku\bu"]
[448.028009, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[448.028773, "o", "\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K\u001b[4mJOURNALCTL\u001b[24m(1)                                              journalctl                                             \u001b[4mJOURNALCTL\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K       journalctl - Print log entries from the systemd journal\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mjournalctl \u001b[22m[OPTIONS...] [MATCHES...]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mjournalctl \u001b[22mis used to print the log entries stored in the journal by \u001b[1msystemd-journald.service\u001b[22m(8) and \u001b[1msystemd-journal-\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mremote.service\u001b[22m(8).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K       If called without parameters, it will show the contents of the journal accessible to the calling user, starting with the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K       oldest entry collected.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K       If one or more match arguments are passed, the output is filtered accordingly. A match is in the format \"FIELD=VALUE\",\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K       e.g. "]
[448.02941, "o", " \"_SYSTEMD_UNIT=httpd.service\", referring to the components of a structured journal entry. See \u001b[1msystemd.journal-\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mfields\u001b[22m(7) for a list of well-known fields. If multiple matches are specified matching different fields, the log entries\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K       are filtered by both, i.e. the resulting output will show only entries matching all the specified matches of this kind.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K       If two matches apply to the same field, then they are automatically matched as alternatives, i.e. the resulting output\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K       will show entries matching any of the specified matches for the same field. Finally, the character \"+\" may appear as a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K\u001b[4mJOURNALCTL\u001b[24m(1)                                              journalctl                                             \u001b[4mJOURNALCTL\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K       journalctl - Print log entries from the systemd journal\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n"]
[448.029508, "o", "\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mjournalctl \u001b[22m[OPTIONS...] [MATCHES...]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mjournalctl \u001b[22mis used to print the log entries stored in the journal by \u001b[1msystemd-journald.service\u001b[22m(8) and \u001b[1msystemd-journal-\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mremote.service\u001b[22m(8).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K       If called without parameters, it will show the contents of the journal accessible to the calling user, starting with the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K       oldest entry collected.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K       If one or more match arguments are passed, the output is filtered accordingly. A match is in the format \"FIELD=VALUE\",\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K       e.g.  \"_SYSTEMD_UNIT=httpd.service\", referring to the components of a structured journal entry. See \u001b[1msystemd.journal-\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mfields\u001b[22m(7) for a list of well-known fields. If multiple matches are specified matching different fields, the log entries\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K       are filtered by both, i.e. the result"]
[448.030061, "o", "ing output will show only entries matching all the specified matches of this kind.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K       If two matches apply to the same field, then they are automatically matched as alternatives, i.e. the resulting output\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K       will show entries matching any of the specified matches for the same field. Finally, the character \"+\" may appear as a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H"]
[448.03044, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       Additional constraints may be added using options \u001b[1m--boot\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mnit=\u001b[22m, etc., to further limit what entries will be shown\u001b[m\r\n       (logical AND).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Output is interleaved from all accessible journal files, whether they are rotated or currently being written, and\u001b[m\r\n       regardless of whether they belong to the system itself or are accessible user journals. The \u001b[1m--header \u001b[22moption can be used\u001b[m\r\n       to identify which files \u001b[4mare\u001b[24m being shown.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The set of journal files which will be used can be modified using the \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1mser\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--system\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--directory=\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1m--file=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       options, see below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       All users are granted access to their private per\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27mser journals. However, by default, only root and users who are\u001b[m\r\n       members of a few special groups are granted access to the system journal and the journals of other users. Members of the\u001b[m\r\n       groups \""]
[448.03051, "o", "systemd-journal\", \"adm\", and \"wheel\" can read all journal files. Note that the two latter groups traditionally\u001b[m\r\n       have additional privileges specified by the distribution. Members of the \"wheel\" group can often perform administrative\u001b[m\r\n       tasks.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The output is paged through \u001b[1mless \u001b[22mby default, and long lines are \"truncated\" to screen width. The hidden part can be\u001b[m\r\n       viewed by using the left-arrow and right-arrow keys. Paging can be disabled; see the \u001b[1m--no-pager \u001b[22moption and the\u001b[m\r\n       \"Environment\" section below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When outputting to a tty, lines are colored according to priority: lines of level ERROR and higher are colored red;\u001b[m\r\n       lines of level WARNING are colored yellow; lines of level NOTICE are highlighted; lines of level INFO are displayed\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 39 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[448.59707, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[448.597146, "o", "       normally; lines of level DEBUG are colored grey.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       To write entries \u001b[4mto\u001b[24m the journal, a few methods may be used. In general, output from systemd units is automatically\u001b[m\r\n       connected to the journal, see \u001b[1msystemd-journald.service\u001b[22m(8). In addition, \u001b[1msystemd-cat\u001b[22m(1) may be used to send messages to\u001b[m\r\n       the journal directly.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSOURCE OPTIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 46 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[448.859989, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K       The following options control where to read journal records from:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--system\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mser\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 49 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[449.010847, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[449.011011, "o", "           Show messages from system services and the kernel (with \u001b[1m--system\u001b[22m). Show messages from service of current user (with\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1mser\u001b[22m). If neither is specified, show all messages that the user can see.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           The \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1mser \u001b[22moption affects how \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mnit= \u001b[22marguments are treated. See \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mnit=\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Note that \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1mser \u001b[22monly works if persistent logging is enabled, via the \u001b[4mStorage=\u001b[24m setting in \u001b[1mjournald.conf\u001b[22m(5).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 205.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-M\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--machine=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Show messages from a running, local container. Specify a container name to connect to.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 209.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-m\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--merge\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Show entries interleaved from all available journals, including remote ones.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 190.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-D \u001b[4m\u001b[22mDIR\u001b[24m, \u001b[1m--directory=\u001b[4m\u001b[22mDIR\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Takes a directory path as argument. If specified, journalctl will operate on the specified journal directory \u001b[4mDIR\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 70 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[449.872111, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[449.87244, "o", "           instead of the default runtime and system journal paths.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 72 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[450.967088, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K           Added in version 187.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 74 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[451.230463, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1m-i \u001b[4m\u001b[22mGLOB\u001b[24m, \u001b[1m--file=\u001b[4m\u001b[22mGLOB\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Takes a file glob as an argument. If specified, journalctl will operate on the specified journal files matching \u001b[4mGLOB\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 76 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[451.455849, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[451.455995, "o", "...skipping...\r\n           hierarchy underneath the specified directory instead of the root directory (e.g.  \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1mpdate-catalog \u001b[22mwill create\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mROOT\u001b[24m/var/lib/systemd/catalog/database, and journal files under \u001b[4mROOT\u001b[24m/run/journal/ or \u001b[4mROOT\u001b[24m/var/log/journal/ will be\u001b[m\r\n           displayed).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 201.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--image=\u001b[4m\u001b[22mIMAGE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Takes a path to a disk image file or block device node. If specified, \u001b[1mjournalctl \u001b[22mwill operate on the file system in\u001b[m\r\n           the indicated disk image. This option is similar to \u001b[1m--root=\u001b[22m, but operates on file systems stored in disk images or\u001b[m\r\n           block devices, thus providing an easy way to extract log data from disk images. The disk image should either contain\u001b[m\r\n           just a file system or a set of file systems within a GPT partition table, following the \u001b[34m\u001b[1mDiscoverable Partitions\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1m\u001b[34mSpecification\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m[1"]
[451.456322, "o", "]. For further information on supported disk images, see \u001b[1msystemd-nspawn\u001b[22m(1)'s switch of the same name.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 247.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--image-policy=\u001b[4m\u001b[22mpolicy\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Takes an image policy string as argument, as per \u001b[1msystemd.image-policy\u001b[22m(7). The policy is enforced when operating on\u001b[m\r\n           the disk image specified via \u001b[1m--image=\u001b[22m, see above. If not specified, defaults to the \"*\" policy, i.e. all recognized\u001b[m\r\n           file systems in the image are used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--namespace=\u001b[4m\u001b[22mNAMESPACE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Takes a journal namespace identifier string as argument. If not specified, the data collected by the default\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 105 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[451.964053, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[451.964312, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       \u001b[1m-S\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--since=\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-U\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mntil=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Start showing entries on or newer than the specified date, or on or older than the specified date, respectively.\u001b[m\r\n           Date specifications should be of the format \"2012-10-30 18:17:16\". If the time part is omitted, \"00:00:00\" is\u001b[m\r\n           assumed. If only the seconds component is omitted, \":00\" is assumed. If the date component is omitted, the current\u001b[m\r\n           day is assumed. Alternatively the strings \"yesterday\", \"today\", \"tomorrow\" are understood, which refer to 00:00:00\u001b[m\r\n           of the day before the current day, the current day, or the day after the current day, respectively.  \"now\" refers to\u001b[m\r\n           the current time. Finally, relative times may be specified, prefixed with \"-\" or \"+\", referring to times before or\u001b[m\r\n           after the current time, respectively. For complete time and date specification, see \u001b[1msystemd.time\u001b[22m(7). No"]
[451.964608, "o", "te that\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1m--output=short-full \u001b[22mprints timestamps that follow precisely this format.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 195.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-c\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--cursor=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Start showing entries from the location in the journal specified by the passed cursor.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 193.\u001b[m\r\n"]
[451.964719, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--after-cursor=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Start showing entries from the location in the journal \u001b[4mafter\u001b[24m the location specified by the passed cursor. The cursor\u001b[m\r\n           is shown when the \u001b[1m--show-cursor \u001b[22moption is used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 206.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 137 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[453.541494, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[453.542161, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mnit=\u001b[4m\u001b[22mUNIT\u001b[24m\u001b[1m|\u001b[4m\u001b[22mPATTERN\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Show messages for the specified systemd unit \u001b[4mUNIT\u001b[24m (such as a service unit), or for any of the units matched by\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24m. If a pattern is specified, a list of unit names found in the journal is compared with the specified pattern\u001b[m\r\n           and all that match are used. For each unit name, a match is added for messages from the unit (\"_SYSTEMD_UNIT=\u001b[4mUNIT\u001b[24m\"),\u001b[m\r\n           along with additional matches for messages from systemd and messages about coredumps for the specified unit. A match\u001b[m\r\n           is also added for \"_SYSTEMD_SLICE=\u001b[4mUNIT\u001b[24m\", such that if the provided \u001b[4mUNIT\u001b[24m is a \u001b[1msystemd.slice\u001b[22m(5) unit, all logs of\u001b[m\r\n           children of the slice will be shown.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           With \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1mser\u001b[22m, all \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mnit= \u001b[22marguments will be converted to match user messages as if specified with \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mser\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mnit=\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This parameter can be specified multiple times.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 195.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1mser\u001b[7m-u\u001b[27m\u001b[1mnit=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Show messages for the specified user session unit. This will add a match for messages from the unit\u001b[m\r\n           (\"_SYSTEMD_USER_UNIT=\" and \"_UID=\") and additional matches for messages from session systemd and messages about\u001b[m\r\n           coredumps for the specified unit. A match is also added for \"_SYSTEMD_USER_SLICE=\u001b[4mUNIT\u001b[24m\", such that if the provided\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mUNIT\u001b[24m is a \u001b[1msystemd.slice\u001b[22m(5) unit, all logs of children of the unit will be shown.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This parameter can be specified multiple times.\u001b[m\r\n"]
[453.542447, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page journalctl(1) line 186 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[466.695788, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[?1l\u001b>\u001b[?1049l\u001b[23;0;0t"]
[466.714493, "o", "\u001b[?2004h\u001b[94m/var/log \u001b(B\u001b[m$ "]
